<subSubSection id="75EC805C67A61C6902B85E59BCBF6909" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="76D2037B0FCF2AD3475FAE36031110CD" pageId="0" pageNumber="255">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C080537EE24DDCD57A214A70927E92AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="255">
Males can be recognized by the tubercle-shaped ridges on posterior part of sternum (arrow in 
<figureCitation id="AD010350912F2A329BCA7231631C4DD8" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Opopaea berlandi, male. A, C, E habitus, dorsal, lateral and ventral views B, D, F, G prosoma, dorsal, lateral, ventral and anterior views H, I abdomen, lateral and anterior views. Abbreviations: boc = booklung covers; dte = dorsolateral, triangular extensions; sr = scutal ridge. Scale bars: 0.4 mm (A, C, E); 0.2 mm (B, D, F-I)." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/350625" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure1">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
), the very small booklung covers (
<figureCitation id="AA2285522B763A52169FD6F1BCD5C061" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Opopaea berlandi, male. A, C, E habitus, dorsal, lateral and ventral views B, D, F, G prosoma, dorsal, lateral, ventral and anterior views H, I abdomen, lateral and anterior views. Abbreviations: boc = booklung covers; dte = dorsolateral, triangular extensions; sr = scutal ridge. Scale bars: 0.4 mm (A, C, E); 0.2 mm (B, D, F-I)." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/350625" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure1">Fig. 1H</figureCitation>
), and the truncate tip of cymbiobulbus (
<figureCitation id="BAD1E7B0188BB9ABC97CC3B8CD84171C" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Opopaea berlandi, male left palp, SEM. A, B prolateral and retrolateral views C, D, G cymbiobulbus, prolateral, retrolateral and dorsal views E, F, H distal part of cymbiobulbus, prolateral, retrolateral and dorsal views." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/350626" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure2">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
); females are recognized by the dark, linguiform projection on the epigastric scutal ridge (lpr in 
<figureCitation id="A7BC558C3B508C4210D7146FFF9747BD" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Female copulatory organ. A, B Opopaea berlandi C, D Opopaea kulczynskii E, F Opopaea sheldrick sp. nov. A, C, E ventral view B, D, F dorsal view. Abbreviations: apo = apodeme; asr = anterior scutal ridge; ga = globular appendix; lpr = linguiform projection; nlp = nail-like process; pd = postgynal depression; pls = paddle-like sclerite; rds = ring-shaped dark spot; sds = stick-shaped dark spot. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/350649" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure23">Fig. 23A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="1431D46F6C06664A491A737AED36FAF8" doi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.39146.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/350625" pageId="0" pageNumber="255" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
